[[1]](#_ftnref1) A Hegelian philosopher (and Marx’s former friend).

[[2]](#_ftnref2) Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen of 1793

[[3]](#_ftnref3) Rights of Man is a book by Thomas Paine first published in 1791, including 31 articles, positing that popular political revolution is permissible when a government does not safeguard the natural rights of its people. Using these points as a base, it defends the French Revolution against Edmund Burke's attack in Reflections on the Revolution in France (1790). It was published in Britain in two parts in March 1791 and February 1792.

[[4]](#_ftnref4) Marx wrote this passage in 1843 as part of the introduction to Critique of Hegel's Philosophy of Right, a book that criticized philosopher Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel's 1820 book, Elements of the Philosophy of Right.

[[5]](#_ftnref5) Shlomo Avineri, The Social and Political Thought of Karl Marx (1968).
